title: Navigation to Google is not working
content:
Hello, it's been a while since this bug started to happen. I was not reporting it becouse it was so eye-catching that I relied on that many others will be reporting this. After a few months without a fix I decided to report the bug as no fix was provided, nor I found any bug report on this.

Reproduction: Click on search bar (not the url bar), press enter. Current behavior: Nothing happens Expected behavior: Go to Google (or any other search engine which is used by the search bar) Current version: Firefox 131.0 (64 bit) Last working version: No idea, was working like 3 or maybe more months ago
creator: jakub.senk

title: Latest version cloaked.  Is something trying to hack Mozilla
content: I have version 130.0.1. I keep getting popups prompting me to update. I'm skeptical at popups so I go to check what is the latest version at Mozilla.com. They don't display that; they only want to automate an update. I won't do that. I want to see what is being updated and to what version before I download and execute some unknown automated process. Mozilla should know better than try to cloak an update on us. We are the ones that use Mozilla because of all the "automated" trouble and hijacks out there.

title: Updated yesterday, and now I can't use it at all!
content:
Yesterday, I installed whatever the current version is for Windows 11. At some point after that, it hung. It wouldn't close, even after doing End Task in task manager, nor shutting down the PC.

When I try to start it, it tells me "Firefox is already running, but not responding. The old Firefox process must be closed to open a new window."

Go to task manager, but the only thing I see related to Firefox is under Details pane. Shows a PID but I can't kill it even using the taskkill command as admin:

C:\Windows\System32>taskkill /im "firefox.exe" /t /f SUCCESS: The process with PID 24344 (child process of PID 19568) has been terminated. SUCCESS: The process with PID 15724 (child process of PID 19568) has been terminated. ERROR: The process with PID 32008 (child process of PID 8260) could not be terminated. Reason: There is no running instance of the task. SUCCESS: The process with PID 19568 (child process of PID 20576) has been terminated.

The PID noted above shows a location of C:\Program Files\Mozilla Firefox\tobedeleted, but if I try to delete it (or any other tmp files with yesterday's date), it says they're open in Firefox and won't let me.

Attempted uninstall and reinstall. Same issues as above. Firefox is now unable to be used. I have a ton of bookmarks that I haven't backed up recently by the way. I do NOT want to lose them.

title: Firefox (Mac) unresponsive, and doesn't load any pages including internal ones such as settings, or about:support, even after complete app reinstall.
content: I have reinstalled Firefox on my Mac many times, completely removed all files using app cleaner, and reset Firefox by holding shift and option on start. Despite this, the app is very slow to launch, and when it does no pages load or render. Opening a new tab freezes the entire app for 15-30 seconds, and when the tab opens it is completely blank. Attempting to browse to a URL does nothing, and the address bar just returns to being empty. Attempting to open settings does nothing, although parts of the app that open separate windows such as the about version info and bookmarks work fine. The only thing I haven't done at this point is completely reinstalling macOS, so maybe there is something wrong with my system config. I first noticed this issue when using the early macOS Sequoia betas, and assumed the app wasn't updated to support it yet. However after updating macOS and completely removing and reinstalling all traces of Firefox, it still doesn't work. I am currently using macOS 15.1 beta, however the issue also persisted on 15.0.

Thank you for your help!

title: Impossibilità di accedere a /usr/local
content:
Sto tentando aggiungere il certificato della CIE a Firefox. Il lettore è stato già correttamente accreditato nel sistema (Ubuntu 24.04.1 LTS) e la CIE correttamente associata. L'applicazione governativa CIE ID funziona correttamente.

Quando cerco di associare il lettore a Firefox in "impostazioni/privacy e sicurezza/sicurezza/certificati/dispositivi di sicurezza" tramite il modulo /usr/local/lib/libcie-pkcs11.so, Firefox risponde "Impossibile aggiungere il modulo". Durante uno dei tentativi il programma ha riportato di non poter accedere alla directory /usr/local/ ; tuttavia ho controllato che ognuna delle directory del percorso /usr/local/lib/ ha come permessi "drwxr-x-r-x" e il file libcie-pkcs11.so è tranquillamente leggibile, tramite "hexdump -C -n 10", da terminale.

Qualcuno ha qualche idea?

Grazie,

Renzo Venturi
creator: rventuri

content:

The new tab button is gone, the forward and back buttons are on the right hand side (usually they are on the left), and the bookmarks window is gone. I can then "refresh firefox" to have it revert to the correct setup.

Is there a way to stop this from happening. I restart my PC often, it would be nice for firefox to not do this

content:

title: What best practices should be followed to optimize performance and ensure cross-browser compatibility in complex web applications using modern frameworks?
content:
To optimize performance and ensure cross-browser compatibility in complex web applications, several best practices can be implemented: 

   Use Responsive Design: Employ responsive web design techniques to ensure that your application functions well on various screen sizes and devices. This approach enhances user experience across different platforms. 
   Minimize HTTP Requests: Reduce the number of HTTP requests by combining files (like CSS and JavaScript) and using image sprites. This can significantly improve loading times. 
   Leverage Browser Caching: Implement caching strategies to store frequently accessed resources, which can speed up load times for returning users. 
   Test Across Multiple Browsers: Regularly test your application on various browsers (like Chrome, Firefox, Safari, and Edge) to identify and fix compatibility issues early in the development process. 
   Optimize Images and Assets: Use appropriate image formats and compression techniques to reduce file sizes without compromising quality, which can enhance loading speed. 
   Utilize Best Application Development Services: Partner with experts who provide the best application development services to incorporate performance monitoring and optimization tools into your development workflow.

By following these practices, developers can create robust applications that not only perform well but also deliver a consistent experience across different browsers. Engaging with the community to share insights and experiences can further enhance our collective understanding of effective application development strategies.
creator: adamjes88

title: Denied Error
content:
Trying to put Albertsons.com in browser and it comes up with

Access denied Error 16 www.albertsons.com 2024-10-03 06:13:30 UTC What happened? This request was blocked by our security service Your IP: 216.131.81.135 Proxy IP: 45.60.12.113 (ID 101449-100) Incident ID: 1449000070080309759-206631203123036621

Why? I haven't had trouble before. Dianan

title: Password Manager Does Not Work Properly on Wix
content:
The way the FF browser saves the password only links to the basic URL, users.wix.com. The problem being, it only offers the password options if one the sign up users page, which that URL default to. It will show the drop down menu with your login options. Once selecting login, FF no longer offers any password options, even with a right-click. Wix has a two page login, one with email, then the next with the password. It is like FF does not even recognize that first page properly. Only after manually entering the email, does the password just appear on the second page (if saved).

This is really sloppy functionality. It really stinks if it has been awhile since logging in, and you cannot remember what email was used with the account if several are related. It requires then manually going into setting and looking it up in the passwords section. I have never experienced this problem with other browsers.

It is there any way to get it to work normally with Wix (and possibly other similar two-step logins)?

title: Video content jiggles about on crunchyroll.com
content:
Hi all,

I have jumped ship from Chrome to Firefox today but I have encountered an issue with the site crunchyroll.com where the video content will jiggle around during playback (both full-screen and regular page view.) I have tested Youtube as well and the issue is not present on those videos. To give you a better picture of what it is like, it is like watching a video on an OLED screen with pixel shift enabled but it's super aggresive and is incredibly distracting.

To my memory I am pretty confident that the video player used on Crunyroll's website is a HTML5 player with DRM security and videos are in mp4 format.

I am running Firefox 131.0 (64-bit) completly fresh on Windows 11 with an RTX 30 series GPU. So far I have tried the following with no success and the jiggle remaining:

  1. Cleared the site data and cache
  2. Disabled Add-ons one-by-one to identify a potential culprit
  3. Disabled Hardware acceleration
  4. Ran Firefox in Safe Mode
  5. All of the above in combination

I am stumped as to why this might be happening especially with a fresh out-of-box experiance. Any assistance you can provide on this would be greatly appreciated, as I would prefer to avoid Chromium browsers going forward.

Many thanks, Phreaky
creator: Phreaky

title: Mozilla Firefox since v127.0 cannot install anymore the Adobe Acrobat Pro extension (adobe_acrobat-1.0-windows.xpi)
content:
Since Mozilla Firefox web browser v127.0 (released June 11 2024) the manual installation of the Adobe Acrobat Pro extension (the adobe_acrobat-1.0-windows.xpi file) do not work anymore!  :disappointed_face:

So, when you go in any higher version of Mozilla Firefox web browser then v126.0.1 (released May 28, 2024) to this web browser Menu Bar -> Tools -> Add-ons and Themes -> Extensions -> Install Add-on From File..., and then try to manually import-install the Adobe Acrobat Pro extension (the adobe_acrobat-1.0-windows.xpi file) into the Mozilla Firefox web browser, and from this HDD location:

C:\Program Files (x86)\Adobe\Acrobat DC\Acrobat\Browser\WCFirefoxExtn\WebExtn\signed_extn\adobe_acrobat-1.0-windows.xpi

The Mozilla Firefox web browser will say during this .xpi file installation: "This add on could not be installed because it appears to be corrupt"!  :disappointed_face:

However, in any Mozilla Firefox web browser version prior v127.0 (released June 11 2024), this manual import-installation of the adobe_acrobat-1.0-windows.xpi file will be most successfully installed in a Mozilla Firefox web browser without any problem!

I also create the most detailed and step-by-step post on the Mozillazine.org Forum and the Adobe Forum about all of this problem:

https://community.adobe.com/t5/acrobat-discussions/mozilla-firefox-since-v127-0-cannot-install-anymore-the-adobe-acrobat-pro-xpi-extension/m-p/14893786#M480889


So, please help and advice further. Thank you in advance and best regards!
creator: Brus
